# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# CODEOWNERS — the ONE hard gate in the Centre of Excellence
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# Read this before changing it.
#
# The library is deliberately LIGHT and ADVISORY. There is no approval gate
# anywhere in the library, and NOTHING at the downstream-project level is
# enforced here — each project runs in its own GitHub Project, guided by these
# skills, and decides for itself. The skills nudge; they never block.
#
# There are exactly TWO places where a human's review is made STRUCTURALLY
# necessary, and they are here: adding or changing a component PATTERN, or a
# CAPABILITY, requires review from a human architect before it can merge. That
# requirement is expressed entirely in GitHub mechanics — this CODEOWNERS file
# PLUS a branch protection rule on the default branch with "Require review from
# Code Owners" turned on.
#
# WHY a pattern (and a capability) gets a hard gate:
#   A pattern is a load-bearing claim. When a downstream project adopts one, the
#   pattern's governed NFRs propagate into that project's requirements, its
#   constraints get replayed during validation, and its "used in N engagements"
#   provenance legitimises a fast-track. An unreviewed pattern is therefore the
#   one artefact that can quietly do harm at scale. So a pattern must be:
#     - PR-reviewed and validated by a human architect (this file),
#     - carry evidence/artefacts that it was actually built,
#     - carry approved_at + validity_check_months + sunset_at/superseded_by metadata
#       (validated by the frontmatter-check Action — advisory CI, not a gate).
#   A capability is the need-side mirror: it names a need and records which
#   components fulfil it (proven, with evidence) or only might (candidate, with
#   spikes owed). Flipping a fulfilment to `proven`, like promoting a pattern, is
#   a human-only act gated here. The CI Action checks shape; the architect review
#   checks SUBSTANCE. Only the human can set the equivalent of `approved_by` —
#   agents enumerate, compute, and propose, but never bless a pattern or
#   capability. CODEOWNERS is how that human-in-the-loop is made structural.
#
# Everything else below routes to the team that maintains it for ordinary
# review hygiene — none of those routes is a "gate" in the governance sense;
# they just make sure the right humans see changes to shared machinery.
#
# ─── HOW TO ACTIVATE ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#   1. Replace the placeholder @org/team handles below with REAL GitHub teams.
#      (They must be teams in this repo's org, each with at least write access,
#       or CODEOWNERS review cannot be required.)
#   2. In Settings → Branches → branch protection for the default branch:
#        ✓ Require a pull request before merging
#        ✓ Require review from Code Owners
#      That single checkbox + the /patterns/** and /capabilities/** lines below
#      IS the gate.
#   3. Leave everything else advisory. Resist adding enforcement.
#
# NOTE: matching is last-match-wins, so order matters. More specific paths
#       are placed AFTER the broader ones they refine.
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────


# ─── THE HARD GATE ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Component patterns: a human architect must review every add/change.
# Combined with branch protection, this blocks a merge. Patterns carry
# propagatable NFRs + replayable constraints + adoption provenance — they earn
# the gate. (Placeholder: set @org/architects to your real architecture-review
# team.)
/patterns/**                @org/architects

# Capabilities: the need-side mirror of patterns — same hard gate, same team.
# A capability names a need and records proven|candidate fulfilments; flipping a
# fulfilment to `proven` is a human-only act, so capability changes get the same
# architect review as patterns.
/capabilities/**            @org/architects


# ─── ADVISORY ROUTES (review hygiene, NOT gates) ─────────────────────────────

# The portable agent skills. Maintained by the CoE maintainers; reviewed, not
# gated.
/skills/**                  @org/coe-maintainers

# The NFR catalogue — shared vocabulary that patterns attach to. Owned by the
# platform team because a change here ripples into every pattern's attached_nfrs
# and the frontmatter validator's allowed `kind` enum.
/nfrs/**                    @org/platform

# Repo machinery: Actions (concatenate-related-patterns, validate-frontmatter),
# templates, this CODEOWNERS file itself. Platform-owned so the automated steps
# and the gate definition can't drift unnoticed.
/.github/**                 @org/platform

# The pattern SCHEMA (frontmatter contract the CI Action validates against).
# Platform-owned even though it lives under /patterns/, because it defines the
# shape ALL patterns must satisfy — it is machinery, not a pattern. Placed after
# the /patterns/** line so this more-specific rule wins (last match wins).
/patterns/_schema/**        @org/platform

# The capability SCHEMA — same reasoning as the pattern schema: it defines the
# shape ALL capabilities must satisfy, so it is platform machinery, not a
# capability. Placed after /capabilities/** so this more-specific rule wins.
/capabilities/_schema/**    @org/platform
